{
  "model": "blog.post",
  "pk": 1,
  "fields": {
    "title": "What I Learned Setting Up Django for the First Time",
    "slug": "what-i-learned-setting-up-django-for-the-first-tim",
    "excerpt": "Setting up Django felt overwhelming at first. Here's everything I wish someone had told me before I started.",
    "body": "I'm an electrical engineering student at FUTO, and a few weeks ago I decided to build my own portfolio website using Django. I had used HTML and CSS before, but Django was a completely different world. Here's what I learned going through the setup process for the first time.\r\n\r\nVirtual Environments Are Not Optional\r\n\r\nThe first thing I had to understand was virtual environments. Before Django, I would just install Python packages directly on my computer. Django taught me why that's a bad idea. Every project needs its own isolated environment with its own packages so projects don't interfere with each other.\r\n\r\nThe commands that changed everything for me:\r\n\r\npython -m venv venv\r\nvenv\\Scripts\\activate\r\npip install django\r\n\r\nOnce I saw (venv) appear in my terminal, I knew I was doing it properly.\r\n\r\nDjango's Folder Structure Confused Me At First\r\n\r\nWhen you run django-admin startproject, Django creates folders inside folders, and it looks overwhelming. I kept asking myself, \"What is WSGI?\" py? Why is there a folder with the same name as my project?\r\n\r\nThe simple way I now think about it is this. The outer folder is just your workspace. The inner folder with the same name is Django's brain—settings, URLs, and configuration. Your apps are where your actual code lives.\r\n\r\nTemplates Must Be In The Right Place\r\n\r\nThis one cost me the most time. I kept getting TemplateDoesNotExist errors even when I was sure the file existed. The problem was always one of two things—either the templates folder was in the wrong location, or I forgot to add the app to INSTALLED_APPS in settings. py.\r\n\r\nThe fix is simple once you know it. Your templates folder must sit at the root of your project and settings. py must point to it like this:\r\n\r\n'DIRS': [BASE_DIR / 'templates'],\r\n\r\nThe .env File Is Important From Day One One\r\n\r\nI learned the hard way not to put passwords and secret keys directly in settings. py. The moment you push your code to GitHub, everyone can see it. Using python-decouple and a .env file keeps your secrets safe and your code clean.\r\n\r\nWhat Surprised Me Most\r\n\r\nDjango does a lot of heavy lifting for you. The admin panel alone—which you get for free with zero extra code—saves hours of work. You can add projects, write blog posts, and manage contact messages all from a clean interface without touching the database directly.\r\n\r\nIf you're an engineering student thinking about learning web development, Django is worth it. It teaches you to think in systems—models, views, templates, URLs—and that kind of thinking transfers to every other area of programming.\r\n\r\nI'm still learning. But setting up this portfolio was the best coding decision I've made so far.",
    "image": "blog/django_piwfEOg.png",
    "created_at": "2026-04-03T22:13:46.890Z",
    "updated_at": "2026-04-03T22:40:21.899Z",
    "published": true
  }
}
